The courts remained a central arena where these cross-pressures met. A three-judge panel at the Court of International Trade ruled that Trump\'92s tariffs were illegal because the Constitution reserves tariff power to Congress, even as appeals courts paused the effect of that ruling. A federal judge ordered the administration to release funds to Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty, reinforcing Congress\'92s control over appropriations. Another judge denied the administration\'92s request for more time in a lawsuit over the rendition of Kilmar Abrego Garcia to El Salvador, chastising officials for delay. Yet the Supreme Court, in an 8\'960 ruling, narrowed the scope of environmental review under the National Environmental Policy Act in a case involving a Utah oil railway, and allowed the administration to revoke temporary protected status and parole programs for hundreds of thousands of migrants. The judiciary, in short, was not a single actor but a field of conflict, with lower courts often resisting and the high court more often aligning with executive and industry interests.\
